.\" Manpage for cpk
.TH CPK 1 "April 2026" "cpk 0.3" "CRUX Package Keeper Manual"
.SH NAME
cpk \- CRUX Package Keeper - Package management tool for CRUX Linux
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B cpk
<command> [options]
.br
.B cpk help
[<command>]
.SH DESCRIPTION
CRUX Package Keeper is a toolset designed to efficiently manage packages and their sources in CRUX environments.

.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B update
Update the index of available packages, then ensure a \fB.cpk.info\fR sidecar exists in the cache for each index entry: existing valid files are left unchanged; missing or unreadable ones are downloaded. Prints counts of new and updated metadata (vs. the previous cache) for packages that were fetched this run, each followed by the matching index entries (without the \fB.cpk\fR suffix).
.TP
.B info
<package> [\fI\-\-name\fR | \fI\-\-version\fR | \fI\-\-arch\fR | \fI\-\-description\fR | \fI\-\-url\fR | \fI\-\-dependencies\fR]
Show information about installed or available packages. Attempts to download the .cpk.info file first (faster), falling back to downloading the full .cpk archive if needed. Use field filters to show only specific information.
.TP
.B deps
<package>
Show package dependencies (alias for \fBinfo\fR \fI\-\-dependencies\fR).
.TP
.B deptree
<package>
.br
.B deptree
<path/to/package.cpk>
Print a recursive dependency tree using repository metadata (or a local .cpk), similar to \fBprt\-get deptree\fR. Each line is prefixed with \fB[i]\fR if the package appears installed, \fB[ ]\fR otherwise. A dependency already shown earlier in the tree is listed again with \fB\-\->\fR instead of expanding its subtree.
.TP
.B search
<keyword>
Search for packages by name or keyword.
.TP
.B list
List all installed packages.
.TP
.B diff
Show differences between installed and available packages.
.TP
.B verify <package>
Verify integrity of package source files.
.TP
.B build <package>
Build a package from source files.
.TP
.B install
[\fI\-\-upgrade\fR] [\fI\-\-no\-deps\fR] <package>
.br
.B install
[\fI\-\-upgrade\fR] [\fI\-\-no\-deps\fR] <path/to/package.cpk>
Install or upgrade packages on the system. By default reads metadata from the repository (or the local .cpk), resolves direct dependencies recursively, and installs those dependencies before the requested package. Use \fI\-\-no\-deps\fR to install only the named package. Use \fI\-\-upgrade\fR to upgrade an already installed package; \fI\-\-upgrade\fR applies only to the package given on the command line, not to dependencies pulled in automatically.
.TP
.B add
[\fI\-\-upgrade\fR] [\fI\-\-no\-deps\fR] <package>
.br
.B add
[\fI\-\-upgrade\fR] [\fI\-\-no\-deps\fR] <path/to/package.cpk>
Alias for \fBinstall\fR (same options and behavior).
.TP
.B uninstall
<package>
Remove packages from the system.
.TP
.B del
<package>
Alias for \fBuninstall\fR.
.TP
.B rm
<package>
Alias for \fBuninstall\fR.
.TP
.B upgrade
[<package>...]
Upgrade all or specific installed packages to the latest versions. If no package names are provided, upgrades all installed packages.
.TP
.B clean
Clean up package source files and temporary directories.
.TP
.B index <repo>
Create a CPKINDEX file for a local repository.
.TP
.B archive <prtdir> <repo>
Create .cpk archive(s) from a directory containing ports.
.TP
.B help
[<command>]
Show help message or detailed help for a specific command. Use \fBcpk help <command>\fR to see detailed information about a specific command.
.TP
.B version
Show version information.

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-c, \-\-config <file>
Set an alternative configuration file (default: /etc/cpk.conf).
.TP
.B \-r, \-\-root <path>
Set an alternative installation root (default: /).
.TP
.B \-C, \-\-color
Show colorized output messages.
.TP
.B \-v, \-\-verbose
Show verbose output messages.
.TP
.B \-h, \-\-help
Print this help information.

.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Update package index:
.B cpk update
.TP
Show all information about a package:
.B cpk info vim
.TP
Show only the version of a package:
.B cpk info vim --version
.TP
Show package dependencies:
.B cpk deps vim
.TP
Show recursive dependency tree:
.B cpk deptree vim
.TP
Search for a package:
.B cpk search curl
.TP
Install a package:
.B cpk install htop
.TP
Install a package from a local .cpk file:
.B cpk install /tmp/mypackage#4.1.0-1.i686.cpk
.br
.B sudo cpk add /tmp/mypackage#4.1.0-1.i686.cpk
.TP
Upgrade an installed package:
.B cpk install --upgrade htop
.br
.B cpk add --upgrade htop
.TP
Uninstall a package:
.B cpk uninstall htop
.br
.B cpk rm htop
.TP
Upgrade all packages:
.B cpk upgrade
.TP
Upgrade specific packages:
.B cpk upgrade vim htop
.TP
List installed packages:
.B cpk list
.TP
Get detailed help for a command:
.B cpk help info
.br
.B cpk help install

.SH AUTHOR
Written by Jose Beneyto (https://github.com/sepen/cpk)

.SH SEE ALSO
.BR pkgmk (8),
.BR pkgadd (8),
.BR pkgrm (8),
.BR prt-get (8)

.SH FILES
When installed from the source distribution, shell completion files are installed as
\fIPREFIX\fR/share/bash-completion/completions/cpk
and
\fIPREFIX\fR/share/zsh/site-functions/_cpk .
For
.BR bash (1),
ensure bash-completion loads files from that directory (many distributions do by default).
For
.BR zsh (1),
add the site-functions directory to
.B fpath
before
.B compinit
if needed.
